    <!-- Add insight / key takeaway directly related to activity / learner experience -->
   <axiom component="lesson-plan">
    <title>Structured Instruction</title>
    <p>
        <dl>
            <li>
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p>10 minutes</p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Objective</title>
                <p>
                    To formalize the concepts and properties learners discovered in the anchor task.
                </p>
            </li>
        </dl>
    </p>
    <paragraphs>
        <title>Key Takeaways &amp; Teacher Connection</title>
        <ol>
            <li>
                <p>
                    <alert>Connecting to Learner Work:</alert> Group the measurements found by the class during the activity. Highlight that regardless of where point <m>C</m> was placed, the angle consistently measured exactly <m>90^\circ</m>. Formalize this as Thales's Theorem: <em>The angle subtended by a diameter at the circumference of a circle is always a right angle.</em>
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    <alert>Mathematical Proof Connection:</alert> Connect this back to the core circle theorem: <em>The angle subtended by an arc at the center is twice the angle subtended at the circumference</em>. Since a straight-line diameter forms a <m>180^\circ</m> angle at the center <m>O</m>, the angle at the circumference must be:
                    <me>\frac{180^\circ}{2} = 90^\circ</me>
                </p>
            </li>
        </ol>
    </paragraphs>
</axiom>

<insight>
    <title>Key Insight: The Right-Triangle Hidden in the Circle</title>
    <p>
        Whenever you see a triangle inscribed inside a circle where one side is explicitly stated to be the <alert>diameter</alert>, you can automatically mark the opposite interior angle at the circumference as a <alert>right angle</alert> measuring <m>90^\circ</m>. This foundational concept acts as a gateway that bridges circle geometry directly with the <alert>Pythagorean theorem</alert> and <alert>trigonometric ratios</alert> such as <m>\sin</m>, <m>\cos</m>, and <m>\tan</m>.
    </p>
    <!-- <figure xml:id="fig-thales-theorem-insight">
        <caption>Angles subtended by the diameter line AB at various points on the circumference (C, D, and E) consistently equal 90 degrees.</caption>
        <image source="images/angles-subtended-diameter.png" width="80%">
            <description>A circle with center O and horizontal diameter AB. Inscribed triangles ACB, ADB, and AEB are shown, with points C, D, and E on the circumference. Each inscribed angle is marked with a right-angle square symbol and labeled 90 degrees.</description>
        </image>
    </figure> -->
</insight>

    <!-- <insight>
    </insight> -->

    <!-- Add further instruction (not in a block) to develop ideas as needed -->

    <xi:include href="../lesson-plan-templates/example-intro.ptx" />

    <!-- Add at least 3 examples -->
    <example>
    <!-- <title>Example 1: Finding a Missing Angle</title> -->
    <statement>
        <p>
            In a circle with center <m>O</m>, <m>PQ</m> is the diameter. A point <m>R</m> lies on the circumference such that <m>\angle RPQ = 34^\circ</m>. Determine the magnitude of <m>\angle PQR</m>.
        </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
        <p>
            1. Identify the angle subtended by the diameter: Since <m>PQ</m> is the diameter, <m>\angle PRQ = 90^\circ</m> (Angle subtended by diameter).
        </p>
        <p>
            2. Use the sum of angles in <m>\triangle PQR</m>:
            <me>\angle RPQ + \angle PRQ + \angle PQR = 180^\circ</me>
            <me>34^\circ + 90^\circ + \angle PQR = 180^\circ</me>
        </p>
        <p>
            3. Solve for <m>\angle PQR</m>:
            <me>\angle PQR = 180^\circ - 124^\circ = 56^\circ</me>
        </p>
    </solution>
</example>

<example>
    <!-- <title>Example 2: Combining with Algebraic Expressions</title> -->
    <statement>
        <p>
            Line <m>AB</m> passes through the center <m>O</m> of a circle. Point <m>C</m> is on the circumference. If <m>\angle CAB = 2x</m> and <m>\angle CBA = 3x - 5^\circ</m>, find the value of <m>x</m>.
        </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
        <p>
            1. Since <m>AB</m> passes through the center <m>O</m>, it is a diameter. Therefore, <m>\angle ACB = 90^\circ</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
            2. Set up the interior angles equation for <m>\triangle ABC</m>:
            <me>2x + (3x - 5^\circ) + 90^\circ = 180^\circ</me>
            <me>5x + 85^\circ = 180^\circ</me>
        </p>
        <p>
            3. Isolate <m>x</m>:
            <me>5x = 95^\circ</me>
            <me>x = 19^\circ</me>
        </p>
    </solution>
</example>

<example>
    <!-- <title>Example 3: Integrating the Pythagorean Theorem</title> -->
    <statement>
        <p>
            <m>XY</m> is the diameter of a circle with center <m>O</m>. Point <m>Z</m> is on the circumference such that chord <m>XZ = 6\text{ cm}</m> and chord <m>YZ = 8\text{ cm}</m>. Calculate the radius of the circle.
        </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
        <p>
            1. Because <m>XY</m> is the diameter, <m>\triangle XYZ</m> is a right-angled triangle with <m>\angle XZY = 90^\circ</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
            2. Apply the Pythagorean theorem to find the hypotenuse <m>XY</m>:
            <me>XY^2 = XZ^2 + YZ^2</me>
            <me>XY^2 = 6^2 + 8^2 = 36 + 64 = 100</me>
            <me>XY = \sqrt{100} = 10\text{ cm}</me>
        </p>
        <p>
            3. The diameter is <m>10\text{ cm}</m>, so the radius (<m>r</m>) is:
            <me>r = \frac{XY}{2} = \frac{10}{2} = 5\text{ cm}</me>
        </p>
    </solution>
</example>
<example>
    <!-- <title>Example 4: The Circular Sports Field Shortcut</title> -->
    <statement>
        <p>
            A school has a perfectly circular sports field. A straight running track represents the diameter <m>AB</m> of the field. A student stands at a flagpost located at point <m>C</m> on the boundary fence. The student measures the angle from their position to the two endpoints of the diameter track. If <m>\angle CAB = 42^\circ</m>, calculate the angle <m>\angle CBA</m>.
        </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
        <p>
            1. Identify the hidden geometric property: Because the running track <m>AB</m> is a diameter of the circular field, the angle subtended at the boundary point <m>C</m> must be a right angle. Therefore, <m>\angle ACB = 90^\circ</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
            2. Apply the interior angle sum theorem for <m>\triangle ABC</m>:
            <me>\angle CAB + \angle ACB + \angle CBA = 180^\circ</me>
            <me>42^\circ + 90^\circ + \angle CBA = 180^\circ</me>
        </p>
        <p>
            3. Solve for the remaining angle <m>\angle CBA</m>:
            <me>\angle CBA = 180^\circ - 132^\circ = 48^\circ</me>
        </p>
    </solution>
</example>

<example>
    <!-- <title>Example 5: Structural Alignment of a Car Wheel Rim</title> -->
    <statement>
        <p>
            A mechanic uses a computer balancing alignment rig on a circular car wheel rim. The computer identifies a straight diameter line segment across the rim labeled <m>XY</m>. Two structural reinforcement spokes connect from points <m>X</m> and <m>Y</m> to a single outer valve point <m>Z</m> on the edge of the rim. If the lengths of these spokes are represented by algebraic expressions where <m>\angle XZY = 5a - 10^\circ</m> and <m>\angle ZXY = 2a</m>, determine the value of <m>a</m>.
        </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
        <p>
            1. Apply Thales's Theorem to the wheel setup: Since <m>XY</m> is the diameter of the circular rim, the angle subtended at the outer valve point <m>Z</m> on the circumference must equal <m>90^\circ</m>.
            <me>\angle XZY = 90^\circ</me>
        </p>
        <p>
            2. Equate the expression to find the scalar variable <m>a</m>:
            <me>5a - 10^\circ = 90^\circ</me>
            <me>5a = 100^\circ</me>
            <me>a = 20^\circ</me>
        </p>
        <p>
            3. Check consistency using the remaining angle <m>\angle ZXY</m>:
            <me>\angle ZXY = 2(20^\circ) = 40^\circ</me>
            The setup remains a valid right-angled triangle since the acute angles sum up to <m>90^\circ</m> (<m>40^\circ + 50^\circ = 90^\circ</m>).
        </p>
    </solution>
</example>

<example>
    <statement>
        <p>
            A packaging engineer designs a novelty triangular pizza slice box that fits exactly inside a semi-circular transparent lid. The straight baseline of the box is the diameter <m>MN</m> of the circle and measures <m>13\text{ cm}</m>. The vertex corner of the pizza slice touches the curved lid edge at point <m>P</m>. If the shorter cardboard side wall <m>MP</m> is <m>5\text{ cm}</m> long, calculate the length of the remaining side wall <m>NP</m>.
        </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
        <p>
            1. Establish the right-angle framework: Because the baseline <m>MN</m> is the diameter of the circle, the triangle <m>\triangle MNP</m> formed within the semi-circle is right-angled at the circumference vertex. Thus, <m>\angle MPN = 90^\circ</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
            2. Use the Pythagorean theorem to calculate side wall <m>NP</m>, where diameter <m>MN</m> acts as the hypotenuse:
            <me>MN^2 = MP^2 + NP^2</me>
            <me>13^2 = 5^2 + NP^2</me>
            <me>169 = 25 + NP^2</me>
        </p>
        <p>
            3. Isolate and solve for <m>NP</m>:
            <me>NP^2 = 169 - 25 = 144</me>
            <me>NP = \sqrt{144} = 12\text{ cm}</me>
            The length of the remaining cardboard side wall is <m>12\text{ cm}</m>.
        </p>
    </solution>
</example>
